# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: node-fetch-http
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Ajax is not a technology, but rather a programming pattern.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] HTML and CSS can be used in combination to mark up and style information.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] The webpage can be modified by JavaScript to dynamically display (and allow the user to interact with) the new information.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] The built-in XMLHttpRequest object is used to execute Ajax on webpages, allowing websites to load content onto the screen without refreshing the page.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] In the early-to-mid 1990s, most websites were based on complete HTML pages.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Each user action required a complete new page to be loaded from the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] This process was inefficient, as reflected by the user experience: all page content disappeared, then the new page appeared.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Each time the browser reloaded a page because of a partial change, all the content had to be re-sent, even though only some of the information had changed.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] This placed additional load on the server and made bandwidth a limiting factor in performance.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] The foundations of AJAX originate back in 1996 with the introduction of JavaScript 1.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Developers quickly discovered that any HTML element which accepted a "src" attribute could be used to fetch remote data.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] By changing the src of a hidden frame, a developer could fetch remote data, process or display it without a page refresh.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] The remote data could be a string, JavaScript code, XML or a partial HTML page generated on the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] The same could be done with `<img>` and `<embed>` tags, but many developers were alarmed at the concept of an executable GIF and preferred to use the hidden `<iframe>`.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] This technique was used for both Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer, the two main browsers at the time, until developers discovered the XMLHTTP server object (MSXML 1.0) was included in Internet Explorer 4.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Browser detection was then used to either implement the hidden `<iframe>` in Netscape or use the XMLHTTP (MSXML 1.0) object in IE 4.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] In 1996, the iframe tag was introduced by Internet Explorer; like the object element, it can load a part of the web page asynchronously.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] In 1998, the Microsoft Outlook Web Access team developed the concept behind the XMLHttpRequest scripting object.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] It appeared as XMLHTTP in the second version of the MSXML library, which shipped with Internet Explorer 5.0 in March 1999.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] The functionality of the Windows XMLHTTP ActiveX control in IE 5 was later implemented by Mozilla Firefox, Safari, Opera, Google Chrome, and other browsers as the XMLHttpRequest JavaScript object.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Microsoft adopted the native XMLHttpRequest model as of Internet Explorer 7.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Support for the ActiveX version remained in Internet Explorer and on "Internet Explorer mode" in Microsoft Edge.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] The utility of these background HTTP requests and asynchronous Web technologies remained fairly obscure until it started appearing in large scale online applications such as Outlook Web Access (2000) and Oddpost (2002).
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Google made a wide deployment of standards-compliant, cross browser Ajax with Gmail (2004) and Google Maps (2005).
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] In October 2004 Kayak.com's public beta release was among the first large-scale e-commerce uses of what their developers at that time called "the xml http thing".
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] This increased interest in Ajax among web program developers.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] The term *AJAX* was publicly used on 18 February 2005 by Jesse James Garrett in an article titled *Ajax: A New Approach to Web Applications*, based on techniques used on Google pages.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] On 5 April 2006, the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) released the first draft specification for the XMLHttpRequest object in an attempt to create an official Web standard.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] The latest draft of the XMLHttpRequest object was published on 6 October 2016, and the XMLHttpRequest specification is now a living standard.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] The term *Ajax* has come to represent a broad group of Web technologies that can be used to implement a Web application that communicates with a server in the background, without interfering with the current state of the page.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Since then, however, there have been a number of developments in the technologies used in an Ajax application, and in the definition of the term Ajax itself.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] XML is no longer required for data interchange and, therefore, XSLT is no longer required for the manipulation of data.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) is often used as an alternative format for data interchange, although other formats such as preformatted HTML or plain text can also be used.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] A variety of popular JavaScript libraries, including jQuery, include abstractions to assist in executing Ajax requests.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] An example of a simple Ajax request using the GET method, written in JavaScript.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Ajax offers several benefits that can significantly enhance web application performance and user experience.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] By reducing server traffic and improving speed, Ajax plays a crucial role in modern web development.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] One key advantage of Ajax is its capacity to render web applications without requiring data retrieval, resulting in reduced server traffic.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] This optimization minimizes response times on both the server and client sides, eliminating the need for users to endure loading screens.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Furthermore, Ajax facilitates asynchronous processing by simplifying the utilization of XmlHttpRequest, which enables efficient handling of requests for asynchronous data retrieval.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Additionally, the dynamic loading of content enhances the application's performance significantly.
[src:node-fetch-http/ajax-programming] Besides, Ajax enjoys broad support across all major web browsers, including Microsoft Internet Explorer versions 5 and above, Mozilla Firefox versions 1.0 and beyond, Opera versions 7.6 and above, and Apple Safari versions 1.2 and higher.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] It’s been available across browsers since March 2017.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] The **`Request`** interface of the Fetch API represents a resource request.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] You can create a new `Request` object using the `Request()` constructor, but you are more likely to encounter a `Request` object being returned as the result of another API operation, such as a service worker `FetchEvent.request`.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] A `ReadableStream` of the body contents.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Stores `true` or `false` to indicate whether or not the body has been used in a request yet.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Contains the cache mode of the request (e.g., `default`, `reload`, `no-cache`).
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Contains a value controlling whether credentials should be included with the request (e.g., `omit`, `same-origin`, `include`).
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] A string describing the type of content being requested.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] The duplex mode of the request, which determines whether the browser must send the entire request before processing the response.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Contains the associated `Headers` object of the request.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Contains the subresource integrity value of the request (e.g., `sha256-BpfBw7ivV8q2jLiT13fxDYAe2tJllusRSZ273h2nFSE=`).
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] A boolean indicating whether the request is a history navigation.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] A boolean indicating whether the request is a user-triggered reload.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Contains the request's `keepalive` setting (`true` or `false`), which indicates whether the browser will keep the associated request alive if the page that initiated it is unloaded before the request is complete.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Contains the mode for how redirects are handled.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] It may be one of `follow`, `error`, or `manual`.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Contains the referrer of the request (e.g., `client`).
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Contains the referrer policy of the request (e.g., `no-referrer`).
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Returns the `AbortSignal` associated with the request.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Returns the request's target address space, which indicates whether it is a loopback, local, or public request.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with an `ArrayBuffer` representation of the request body.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with a `Blob` representation of the request body.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with a `Uint8Array` representation of the request body.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Creates a copy of the current `Request` object.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with a `FormData` representation of the request body.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with the result of parsing the request body as `JSON`.
[src:node-fetch-http/api-request] Returns a promise that resolves with a text representation of the request body.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] The Fetch API provides a JavaScript interface for making HTTP requests and processing the responses.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Fetch is the modern replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`: unlike `XMLHttpRequest`, which uses callbacks, Fetch is promise-based and is integrated with features of the modern web such as service workers and Cross-Origin Resource Sharing (CORS).
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] With the Fetch API, you make a request by calling `fetch()`, which is available as a global function in both `window` and `worker` contexts.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] You pass it a `Request` object or a string containing the URL to fetch, along with an optional argument to configure the request.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function returns a `Promise` which is fulfilled with a `Response` object representing the server's response.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] You can then check the request status and extract the body of the response in various formats, including text and JSON, by calling the appropriate method on the response.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] We declare a string containing the URL and then call `fetch()`, passing the URL with no extra options.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` function will reject the promise on some errors, but not if the server responds with an error status like `404`: so we also check the response status and throw if it is not OK.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Otherwise, we fetch the response body content as JSON by calling the `json()` method of `Response`, and log one of its values.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that like `fetch()` itself, `json()` is asynchronous, as are all the other methods to access the response body content.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the rest of this page we'll look in more detail at the different stages of this process.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] 2. optionally, an object containing options to configure the request.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this section we'll look at some of the most commonly-used options.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] To read about all the options that can be given, see the `fetch()` reference page.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then `method` must be one of `GET`, `POST` or `HEAD`.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] The request body is the payload of the request: it's the thing the client is sending to the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] You cannot include a body with `GET` requests, but it's useful for requests that send content to the server, such as `POST` or `PUT` requests.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, if you want to upload a file to the server, you might make a `POST` request and include the file as the request body.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Other objects are converted to strings using their `toString()` method.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] See Locked and disturbed streams for more information.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request headers give the server information about the request: for example, in a `POST` request, the `Content-Type` header tells the server the format of the request's body.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] To set request headers, assign them to the `headers` option.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Compared to using plain objects, the `Headers` object provides some additional input sanitization.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] For example, it normalizes header names to lowercase, strips leading and trailing whitespace from header values, and prevents certain headers from being set.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Many headers are set automatically by the browser and can't be set by a script: these are called Forbidden request headers.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the `mode` option is set to `no-cors`, then the set of permitted headers is further restricted.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] `GET` requests don't have a body, but you can still send data to the server by appending it to the URL as a query string.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common way to send form data to the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Whether a request can be made cross-origin or not is determined by the value of the `RequestInit.mode` option.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] This may take one of three values: `cors`, `same-origin`, or `no-cors`.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] See the reference documentation for `RequestInit.mode` for more details.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the context of the Fetch API, a credential is an extra piece of data sent along with the request that the server may use to authenticate the user.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] By default, credentials are only included in same-origin requests.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that if a cookie's `SameSite` attribute is set to `Strict` or `Lax`, then the cookie will not be sent cross-site, even if `credentials` is set to `include`.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Including credentials in cross-origin requests can make a site vulnerable to CSRF attacks, so even if `credentials` is set to `include`, the server must also agree to their inclusion by including the `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` header in its response.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Additionally, in this situation the server must explicitly specify the client's origin in the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` response header (that is, `*` is not allowed).
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Request()` constructor takes the same arguments as `fetch()` itself.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] This means that instead of passing options into `fetch()`, you can pass the same options to the `Request()` constructor, and then pass that object to `fetch()`.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] To make a request cancelable, create an `AbortController`, and assign its `AbortSignal` to the request's `signal` property.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] To cancel the request, call the controller's `abort()` method.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `fetch()` call will reject the promise with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] If the request is aborted after the `fetch()` call has been fulfilled but before the response body has been read, then attempting to read the response body will reject with an `AbortError` exception.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] As soon as the browser has received the response status and headers from the server (and potentially before the response body itself has been received), the promise returned by `fetch()` is fulfilled with a `Response` object.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] The promise returned by `fetch()` will reject on some errors, such as a network error or a bad scheme.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] However, if the server responds with an error like `404`, then `fetch()` fulfills with a `Response`, so we have to check the status before we can read the response body.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] The `Response.status` property tells us the numerical status code, and the `Response.ok` property returns `true` if the status is in the 200 range.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Just like the request, the response has a `headers` property which is a `Headers` object, and this contains any response headers that are exposed to scripts, subject to the exclusions made based on the response type.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] These are all asynchronous methods, returning a `Promise` which will be fulfilled with the body content.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] The method will throw an exception if the response body is not in the appropriate format: for example, if you call `json()` on a response that can't be parsed as JSON.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Request and response bodies are actually `ReadableStream` objects, and whenever you read them, you're streaming the content.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is good for memory efficiency, because the browser doesn't have to buffer the entire response in memory before the caller retrieves it using a method like `json()`.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] This also means that the caller can process the content incrementally as it is received.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] If we use `Response.text()`, as above, we must wait until the whole file has been received before we can process any of it.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this example, we iterate asynchronously over the stream, processing each chunk as it arrives.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] Note that when you access the body directly like this, you get the raw bytes of the response and must transform it yourself.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] In this case we call `ReadableStream.pipeThrough()` to pipe the response through a `TextDecoderStream`, which decodes the UTF-8-encoded body data as text.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] In the example below, we fetch a text resource and process it line by line, using a regular expression to look for line endings.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] This is a common pattern when implementing an offline cache with service workers.
[src:node-fetch-http/fetch-api-using-fetch] The service worker wants to return the response to the app, but also to cache the response.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] The standardization effort was supported by the Chrome, Opera, Firefox, Internet Explorer 11, Safari, Amazon Silk, and Edge browsers.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Most major browsers had added HTTP/2 support by the end of 2015.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] About 97% of web browsers used have the capability (and 100% of "tracked desktop" web browsers).
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] As of July 2023, 36% (after topping out at just over 50%) of the top 10 million websites support HTTP/2.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Its successor is HTTP/3, a major revision that builds on the concepts established by HTTP/2.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] The changes do not require any changes to how existing web applications work, but new applications can take advantage of new features for increased speed.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] HTTP/2 leaves all of HTTP/1.1's high-level semantics, such as methods, status codes, header fields, and URIs, the same.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] What is new is how the data is framed and transported between the client and the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Websites that are efficient minimize the number of requests required to render an entire page by minifying (reducing the amount of code and packing smaller pieces of code into bundles, without reducing its ability to function) resources such as images and scripts.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] However, minification is not necessarily convenient nor efficient and may still require separate HTTP connections to get the page and the minified resources.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] HTTP/2 allows the server to "push" content, that is, to respond with data for more queries than the client requested.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] This allows the server to supply data it knows a web browser will need to render a web page, without waiting for the browser to examine the first response, and without the overhead of an additional request cycle.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Additional performance improvements in the first draft of HTTP/2 (which was a copy of SPDY) come from multiplexing of requests and responses to avoid some of the head-of-line blocking problem in HTTP 1 (even when HTTP pipelining is used), header compression, and prioritization of requests.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] However, as HTTP/2 runs on top of a single TCP connection, there is still potential for head-of-line blocking to occur if TCP packets are lost or delayed in transmission.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] HTTP/2 no longer supports HTTP/1.1's chunked transfer encoding mechanism, as it provides its own, more efficient mechanisms for data streaming.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] SPDY (pronounced like "speedy") was a previous HTTP-replacement protocol developed by a research project spearheaded by Google.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Primarily focused on reducing latency, SPDY uses the same TCP pipe but different protocols to accomplish this reduction.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] The basic changes made to HTTP/1.1 to create SPDY included "true request pipelining without FIFO restrictions, message framing mechanism to simplify client and server development, mandatory compression (including headers), priority scheduling, and even bi-directional communication".
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] The HTTP Working Group considered Google's SPDY protocol, Microsoft's HTTP Speed+Mobility proposal (SPDY based), and Network-Friendly HTTP Upgrade.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] In July 2012, Facebook provided feedback on each of the proposals and recommended HTTP/2 be based on SPDY.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] The initial draft of HTTP/2 was published in November 2012 and was based on a straight copy of SPDY.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] The biggest difference between HTTP/1.1 and SPDY was that each user action in SPDY is given a "stream ID", meaning there is a single TCP channel connecting the user to the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] SPDY split requests into either control or data, using a "simple to parse binary protocol with two types of frames".
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] SPDY showed evident improvement over HTTP, with a new page load speedup ranging from 11% to 47%.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] The development of HTTP/2 used SPDY as a jumping-off point.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Among the many detailed differences between the protocols, the most notable is that HTTP/2 uses a fixed Huffman code-based header compression algorithm, instead of SPDY's dynamic stream-based compression.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] This helps to reduce the potential for compression oracle attacks on the protocol, such as the CRIME attack.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] On February 9, 2015, Google announced plans to remove support for SPDY in Chrome in favor of support for HTTP/2.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] This took effect starting with Chrome 51.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] HTTP/2 is defined for both HTTP URIs (without TLS encryption, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2c**) and HTTPS URIs (over TLS using ALPN extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required, a configuration which is abbreviated as **h2**).
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Although the standard itself does not require usage of encryption, all major client implementations (Chrome, Edge, Firefox, Internet Explorer, Opera, Safari) have stated they will only support HTTP/2 over TLS, which makes encryption de facto mandatory.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] The FreeBSD and Varnish developer Poul-Henning Kamp asserts that the standard was prepared on an unrealistically short schedule, ruling out any basis for the new HTTP/2 other than the SPDY protocol and resulting in other missed opportunities for improvement.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Kamp criticizes the protocol itself for being inconsistent and having needless, overwhelming complexity.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] He also states that the protocol violates the protocol layering principle, for example by duplicating flow control that belongs in the transport layer (TCP).
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] He also suggested that the new protocol should have removed HTTP Cookies, introducing a breaking change.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Initially, some members of the Working Group tried to introduce an encryption requirement in the protocol.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Critics stated that encryption has non-negligible computing costs and that many HTTP applications actually have no need for encryption and their providers have no desire to spend additional resources on it.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Encryption proponents have stated that this encryption overhead is negligible in practice.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Poul-Henning Kamp has criticized the IETF for hastily standardizing Google's SPDY prototype as HTTP/2 due to political considerations.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] In the end the Working Group did not reach consensus over the mandatory encryption, although most client implementations require it, which makes encryption a *de facto* requirement.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] The HTTP/2 protocol also faced criticism for not supporting opportunistic encryption, a measure against passive monitoring similar to the STARTTLS mechanism that has long been available in other Internet protocols like SMTP.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] Critics have stated that the HTTP/2 proposal goes in violation of IETF's own RFC 7258 "Pervasive Monitoring Is an Attack", which also has a status of Best Current Practice 188.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] RFC7258/BCP188 mandates that pervasive monitoring be considered as an attack, and protocols designed by IETF should take steps to protect against passive monitoring (for example, through the use of opportunistic encryption).
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] A number of specifications for opportunistic encryption of HTTP/2 have been provided, of which draft-nottingham-http2-encryption was adopted as an official work item of the working group, leading to the publication of RFC 8164 in May 2017.
[src:node-fetch-http/http-2] This head-of-line blocking in HTTP/2 is now widely regarded as a design flaw, and much of the effort behind QUIC and HTTP/3 has been devoted to reduce head-of-line blocking issues.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a request–response protocol in the client–server model.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A transaction starts with a client submitting a request to the server, the server attempts to satisfy the request and returns a response to the client that describes the disposition of the request and optionally contains a requested resource such as an HTML document or other content.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In a common scenario, a web browser acts as the client, and a web server, hosting one or more websites, is the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web browser is an example of a user agent (UA).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Other types of user agent include the indexing software used by search providers (web crawlers), voice browsers, mobile apps, and other software that accesses, consumes, or displays web content.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is designed to permit intermediate network elements to improve or enable communications between clients and servers.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] High-traffic websites often benefit from web cache servers that deliver content on behalf of upstream servers to improve response time.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Web browsers cache previously accessed web resources and reuse them, whenever possible, to reduce network traffic.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP proxy servers at private network boundaries can facilitate communication for clients without a globally routable address, by relaying messages with external servers.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To allow intermediate HTTP nodes (proxy servers, web caches, etc.) to accomplish their functions, some of the HTTP headers (found in HTTP requests/responses) are managed hop-by-hop whereas other HTTP headers are managed end-to-end (managed only by the source client and by the target web server).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web resource is located by a uniform resource locator (URL), using the Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) schemes *http* and *https*.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] URIs are encoded as hyperlinks in HTML documents, so as to form interlinked hypertext documents.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol has been revised over time.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A version is identified as HTTP/# where # is the version number.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This article covers aspects of all versions but provides primary coverage for HTTP/0.9, HTTP/1.0, and HTTP/1.1.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Separate articles cover HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 in detail.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, a separate TCP connection to the same server is made for every resource request.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, instead a TCP connection can be reused to make multiple resource requests (i.e. of HTML pages, frames, images, scripts, stylesheets, etc.).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 communications therefore experience less latency as the establishment of TCP connections presents considerable overhead, especially under high traffic conditions.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Enhancements added with HTTP/2 allow for less latency and, in most cases, higher speeds than HTTP/1.1 communications.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC + UDP transport protocols instead of TCP.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Only the IP layer is used (which UDP, like TCP, builds on).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This slightly improves the average speed of communications and avoids the occasional problem of TCP connection congestion that can temporarily block or slow down the data flow of all its streams (another form of "*head of line blocking*").
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 is supported by 71% of websites (34.1% HTTP/2 + 36.9% HTTP/3 with backwards compatibility) and supported by almost all web browsers (over 98% of users).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is also supported by major web servers over Transport Layer Security (TLS) using an Application-Layer Protocol Negotiation (ALPN) extension where TLS 1.2 or newer is required.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 is used on 36.9% of websites and is supported by most web browsers, i.e.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] (at least partially) supported by 97% of users.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses QUIC instead of TCP for the underlying transport protocol.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Like HTTP/2, it does not obsolete previous major versions of the protocol.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2019, support for HTTP/3 was first added to Cloudflare and Chrome and also enabled in Firefox.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 has lower latency for real-world web pages and loads faster than HTTP/2, in some cases over three times faster than HTTP/1.1, which is still commonly the only protocol enabled.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTPS, the secure variant of HTTP, is used by more than 85% of websites.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP presumes an underlying and reliable transport layer protocol.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard choice of the underlying protocol prior to HTTP/3 is Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 uses a different transport layer called QUIC, which provides reliability on top of the unreliable User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 and earlier have been adapted to be used over plain unreliable UDP in multicast and unicast situations, forming HTTPMU and HTTPU.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They are used in UPnP and Simple Service Discovery Protocol (SSDP), two protocols usually run on a local area network.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP is a stateless application-level protocol and it requires a reliable network transport connection to exchange data between client and server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP implementations, TCP/IP connections are used using well-known ports (typically port 80 if the connection is unencrypted or port 443 if the connection is encrypted, see also List of TCP and UDP port numbers).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/2, a TCP/IP connection plus multiple protocol channels are used.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/3, the application transport protocol QUIC over UDP is used.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Data is exchanged through a sequence of request–response messages which are exchanged by a session layer transport connection.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP client initially tries to establish a connection, real or virtual, with a server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] An HTTP server listening on the port accepts the connection and then waits for a client's request message.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The client sends its HTTP request message.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Upon receiving the request the server sends back an HTTP response message, which includes header(s) plus a body if it is required.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The body of this response message is typically the requested resource, although an error message or other information may also be returned.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At any time and for many reasons, either the client or server can close the connection.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Closing a connection is usually advertised by one or more HTTP headers in the last request or response.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, the TCP/IP connection is always closed after server response has been sent, so it is never persistent.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.0, the TCP/IP connection should always be closed by server after a response has been sent.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/1.1, a keep-alive-mechanism was officially introduced so that a connection could be reused for more than one request/response.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such persistent connections reduce request latency perceptibly because the client does not need to re-negotiate the TCP 3-Way-Handshake connection after the first request has been sent.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Another positive side effect is that, in general, the connection becomes faster with time due to TCP's slow-start-mechanism.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.1 added also HTTP pipelining in order to further reduce lag time when using persistent connections by allowing clients to send multiple requests before waiting for each response.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Because of this, only HEAD and some GET requests (i.e. limited to real file requests and so with URLs without query string used as a command, etc.) could be pipelined in a safe and idempotent mode.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] After many years of struggling with the problems introduced by enabling pipelining, this feature was first disabled and then removed from most browsers.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Pipelining was also removed because of the announced adoption of HTTP/2.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 extended the usage of persistent connections by multiplexing many concurrent requests/responses through a single TCP/IP connection.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/3 does not use TCP/IP connections but QUIC + UDP.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In HTTP/0.9, a requested resource was always sent in its entirety.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 added headers to manage resources cached by a client in order to allow conditional GET requests.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As a stateless protocol, HTTP does not require the web server to retain information or status about each user for the duration of multiple requests.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a web application needs an application session, it implements it via HTTP cookies, hidden variables in a web form or another mechanism.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Typically, to start a session, an interactive login is performed, and to end a session, a logout is requested by the user.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] These kind of operations use a custom authentication mechanism, not HTTP authentication.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides multiple authentication schemes such as basic access authentication and digest access authentication which operate via a challenge–response mechanism whereby the server identifies and issues a challenge before serving the requested content.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP provides a general framework for access control and authentication, via an extensible set of challenge–response authentication schemes, which can be used by a server to challenge a client request and by a client to provide authentication information.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The authentication mechanisms described above belong to the HTTP protocol and are managed by client and server HTTP software (if configured to require authentication before allowing client access to one or more web resources), and not by the web applications using an application session.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP authentication specification includes realms that provide an arbitrary, implementation-specific construct for further dividing resources common to a given root URI.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The realm value string, if present, is combined with the canonical root URI to form the protection space component of the challenge.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This in effect allows the server to define separate authentication scopes under one root URI.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The most popular way of establishing an encrypted HTTP connection is HTTPS.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Two other methods for establishing an encrypted HTTP connection also exist: Secure Hypertext Transfer Protocol, and using the HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header to specify an upgrade to TLS.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Browser support for these two is, however, nearly non-existent.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This section describes messages for HTTP/1.1.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Later versions, HTTP/2 and HTTP/3, use a binary protocol, where headers are encoded in a single `HEADERS` and zero or more `CONTINUATION` frames using HPACK (HTTP/2) or QPACK (HTTP/3), which both provide efficient header compression.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request or response line from HTTP/1 has also been replaced by several pseudo-header fields, each beginning with a colon (`:`).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] At the highest level, a message consists of a header followed by a body.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header consists of lines of ASCII text; each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Structured data that differs for request vs. response.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] lines (at least 1 for HTTP/1.1); see below.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body consists of data in any format; not limited to ASCII.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The format must match that specified by the `Content-Type` header field if the message contains one.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A body is optional or, in other words, can be blank.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Before HTTP/2, the term *entity* was used to mean the body plus header fields that describe the body.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In particular, not all headers were considered part of the entity.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The term *entity header* referred to a header that was considered part of the entity, and sometimes the body was called the *entity body*.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Modern documentation uses *body* and *header* without using *entity*.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field represents metadata about the containing message.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, the information of a header field is used by software and not shown to the user.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A header field line is formatted as a name-value pair with a colon separator.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Whitespace is not allowed around the name, but leading and trailing whitespace is ignored for the value part.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Unlike a method name that must match exactly (case-sensitive), a header field name is matched ignoring case although often shown with each word capitalized.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the following are header fields for `Host` and `Accept-Language`.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standards do not limit the size of a header field or the number of fields in a message.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, most servers, clients, and proxy software impose limits for practical and security reasons.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, the Apache 2.3 server by default limits the size of each field to 8190 bytes, and there can be at most 100 header fields in a single request.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although deprecated by RFC 7230, in the past, long lines could be split into multiple lines with a continuation line starting with a space or tab character.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request is sent by a client to a server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line includes a method name, a request URI and the protocol version with a single space between each field.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request header fields allow the client to pass additional information beyond the request line, acting as request modifiers (similarly to the parameters of a procedure).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the client, about the target resource, or about the expected handling of the request.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the HTTP/1.1 protocol, all header fields except `Host` are optional.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request line containing only the path name is accepted by servers to maintain compatibility with HTTP clients before the HTTP/1.0 specification in RFC 1945.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol structures transaction as operating on resources.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] What a resource represents, whether pre-existing data or data that is generated dynamically, depends on the implementation of the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Often, the resource corresponds to a file or the output of an executable running on the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request identifies a method (sometimes informally called *verb*) to classify the desired action to be performed on a resource.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.0 specification defined the GET, HEAD, and POST methods as well as listing the PUT, DELETE, LINK and UNLINK methods under additional methods.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] However, the HTTP/1.1 specification added five new methods: PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, and TRACE.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Any client can use any method and the server can be configured to support any combination of methods.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a method is unknown to an intermediate, it will be treated as an unsafe and non-idempotent method.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] There is no limit to the number of methods that can be defined, which allows for future methods to be specified without breaking existing infrastructure.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, WebDAV defined seven new methods and RFC 5789 specified the PATCH method.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A general-purpose web server is required to implement at least GET and HEAD, and all other methods are considered optional by the specification.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is in contrast to HTTP header field names which are case-insensitive.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is for a representation of a resource.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] include the representation data in the body.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] in the response header, without having to transfer the entire representation.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to process a resource in some way.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to create or update a resource with the state in the request.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A distinction from POST is that the client specifies the target location on the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] to the origin server identified by the request target.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Request is for a report of the HTTP methods that are supported for a resource.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This can be used to check the functionality of a web server by requesting '*' instead of a specific resource.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Requests the server to respond with the received request in the response body.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That way a client can see what (if any) changes or additions have been made by intermediaries.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request is to modify a resource according to its partial state in the request.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Compared to PUT, this can save bandwidth by sending only part of a resource's representation instead of all of it.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *safe* if a request with that method has no intended effect on the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, OPTIONS, and TRACE are defined as safe.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In other words, safe methods are intended to be read-only.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods can still have side effects not seen by the client, such as appending request information to a log file or charging an advertising account.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, and PATCH are not safe.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They may modify the state of the server or have other effects such as sending an email.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Such methods are therefore not usually used by conforming web robots or web crawlers; some that do not conform tend to make requests without regard to context or consequences.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Despite the prescribed safety of GET requests, in practice their handling by the server is not technically limited in any way.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Careless or deliberately irregular programming can allow GET requests to cause non-trivial changes on the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is discouraged because of the problems which can occur when web caching, search engines, and other automated agents make unintended changes on the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] For example, a website might allow deletion of a resource through a URL such as *https://example.com/article/1234/delete*, which, if arbitrarily fetched, even using GET, would simply delete the article.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A properly coded website would require a DELETE or POST method for this action, which non-malicious bots would not make.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] One example of this occurring in practice was during the short-lived Google Web Accelerator beta, which prefetched arbitrary URLs on the page a user was viewing, causing records to be automatically altered or deleted *en masse*.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The beta was suspended only weeks after its first release, following widespread criticism.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *idempotent* if multiple identical requests with that method have the same effect as a single such request.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods PUT and DELETE, and safe methods are defined as idempotent.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Safe methods are trivially idempotent, since they are intended to have no effect on the server whatsoever; the PUT and DELETE methods, meanwhile, are idempotent since successive identical requests will be ignored.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A website might, for instance, set up a PUT endpoint to modify a user's recorded email address.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If this endpoint is configured correctly, any requests which ask to change a user's email address to the same email address which is already recorded—e.g. duplicate requests following a successful request—will have no effect.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Similarly, a request to DELETE a certain user will have no effect if that user has already been deleted.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods POST, CONNECT, and PATCH are not necessarily idempotent, and therefore sending an identical POST request multiple times may further modify the state of the server or have further effects, such as sending multiple emails.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In some cases this is the desired effect, but in other cases it may occur accidentally.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A user might, for example, inadvertently send multiple POST requests by clicking a button again if they were not given clear feedback that the first click was being processed.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While web browsers may show alert dialog boxes to warn users in some cases where reloading a page may re-submit a POST request, it is generally up to the web application to handle cases where a POST request should not be submitted more than once.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Note that whether or not a method is idempotent is not enforced by the protocol or web server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is perfectly possible to write a web application in which (for example) a database insert or other non-idempotent action is triggered by a GET or other request.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] To do so against recommendations, however, may result in undesirable consequences, if a user agent assumes that repeating the same request is safe when it is not.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A request method is *cacheable* if responses to requests with that method may be stored for future reuse.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The methods GET, HEAD, and POST are defined as cacheable.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In contrast, the methods PUT, DELETE, CONNECT, OPTIONS, TRACE, and PATCH are not cacheable.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A response is sent to the client by the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The start line of a response consists of the protocol version, a status code and optionally a reason phrase with fields separated by a single space character.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following response start line specifies protocol version `HTTP/1.1`, status code `400` and reason phrase `Bad Request`.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Response header fields allow the server to pass additional information beyond the status line, acting as response modifiers.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] They give information about the server or about further access to the target resource or related resources.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Each response header field has a defined meaning which can be further refined by the semantics of the request method or response status code.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The status code is a three-digit, decimal, integer value that represents the disposition of the server's attempt to satisfy the client's request.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Generally, a client handles a response primarily based on the status code and secondarily on response header fields.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A client may not understand each status code that a server reports but it must understand the class as indicated by the first digit and treat an unrecognized code as equivalent to the x00 code of that class.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was received, continuing process.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request was successfully received, understood, and accepted.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Further action needs to be taken in order to complete the request.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The request cannot be fulfilled due to an issue that the client might be able to control.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The server failed to fulfill an apparently valid request.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard reason phrases are only recommendations.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A web server is allowed to use a localized equivalent.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] If a status code indicates a problem, the user agent might display the reason phrase to the user to provide further information about the nature of the problem.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The standard also allows the user agent to attempt to interpret the reason phrase, though this might be unwise since the standard explicitly specifies that status codes are machine-readable and reason phrases are human-readable.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following demonstrates an HTTP/1.1 request-response transaction for a server at www.example.com, port 80.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/1.0 would use the same messages except for a few missing headers.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] HTTP/2 and HTTP/3 would use the same request-response mechanism but with different representations for HTTP headers.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The following is a request with no body.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It consists of a start line, 6 header fields and a blank line – each terminated with a carriage return and line feed sequence.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Host` header field distinguishes between various DNS names sharing a single IP address, allowing name-based virtual hosting.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] While optional in HTTP/1.0, it is mandatory in HTTP/1.1.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Although not clear in the representation above (due to limitations of this wiki), the blank line at the end results in ending in two line terminator sequences.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Represented as a stream of characters, a shorted version of above shows this more clearly with `<CRLF>` representing a line terminator sequence: `GET / HTTP/1.1<CRLF>Host: www.example.com<CRLF><CRLF>`.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In the following response, the ETag (entity tag) header field is used to determine if a cached version of the requested resource is identical to the current version of the resource on the server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The `Content-Type` header field specifies the Internet media type of the data conveyed by the HTTP message, and `Content-Length` indicates its length in bytes.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP/1.1 webserver publishes its ability to respond to requests for a byte range of the resource by including `Accept-Ranges: bytes`.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This is useful, if the client needs to have only certain portions of a resource sent by the server, which is called byte serving.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When `Connection: close` is sent, it means that the web server will close the TCP connection immediately after the end of the transfer of this response.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Most of the header fields are optional but some are mandatory.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] When header `Content-Length` is missing from a response with a body, then this should be considered an error in HTTP/1.0 but it may not be an error in HTTP/1.1 if header `Transfer-Encoding: chunked` is present.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Chunked transfer encoding uses a chunk size of 0 to mark the end of the content.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some old implementations of HTTP/1.0 omitted the header `Content-Length` when the length of the body was not known at the beginning of the response and so the transfer of data to client continued until server closed the socket.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] `Content-Encoding: gzip` informs the client that the body is compressed per the gzip algorithm.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A content delivery protocol that was displaced by HTTP in the early 1990s.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A Gopher-inspired protocol which mandates privacy-related features.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Tim Berners-Lee and his team at CERN are credited with inventing HTTP, along with HTML and the associated technology for a web server and a client user interface called web browser.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Berners-Lee designed HTTP in order to help with the adoption of his other idea: the "WorldWideWeb" project, which was first proposed in 1989, now known as the World Wide Web.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of HTTP was initiated in 1989 and summarized in a simple document describing the behavior of a client and a server using the first HTTP version, named 0.9.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] That version was subsequently developed, eventually becoming the public 1.0.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Development of early HTTP Request for Comments (RFC) documents started a few years later in a coordinated effort by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), with work later moving to the IETF.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol used had only one method, namely GET, which would request a page from a server.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The response from the server was always an HTML page.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since 1992, a new document was written to specify the evolution of the basic protocol towards its next full version.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It supported both the simple request method of the 0.9 version and the full GET request that included the client HTTP version.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] This was the first of the many unofficial HTTP/1.0 drafts that preceded the final work on HTTP/1.0.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned to revise and publish new versions of the protocol as HTTP/1.0 and HTTP/1.1 within 1995, but, because of the many revisions, that timeline lasted much more than one year.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The HTTP WG planned also to specify a far future version of HTTP called HTTP-NG (HTTP Next Generation) that would have solved all remaining problems, of previous versions, related to performances, low latency responses, etc. but this work started only a few years later and it was never completed.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 1996, RFC 1945 was published as a final HTTP/1.0 revision of what had been used in previous 4 years as a pre-standard HTTP/1.0-draft which was already used by many web browsers and web servers.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In early 1996 developers started to even include unofficial extensions of the HTTP/1.0 protocol (i.e. keep-alive connections, etc.) into their products by using drafts of the upcoming HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Since early 1996, major web browsers and web server developers also started to implement new features specified by pre-standard HTTP/1.1 drafts specifications.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] End-user adoption of the new versions of browsers and servers was rapid.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In March 1996, one web hosting company reported that over 40% of browsers in use on the Internet used the new HTTP/1.1 header "Host" to enable virtual hosting, and that by June 1996, 65% of all browsers accessing their servers were pre-standard HTTP/1.1 compliant.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In January 1997, RFC 2068 was officially released as HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 1999, RFC 2616 was released to include all improvements and updates based on previous (obsolete) HTTP/1.1 specifications.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Resuming the old 1995 plan of previous HTTP Working Group, in 1997 an *HTTP-NG Working Group* was formed to develop a new HTTP protocol named HTTP-NG (HTTP New Generation).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] A few proposals / drafts were produced for the new protocol to use multiplexing of HTTP transactions inside a single TCP/IP connection, but in 1999, the group stopped its activity passing the technical problems to IETF.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2007, the IETF HTTP Working Group (HTTP WG bis or HTTPbis) was restarted firstly to revise and clarify previous HTTP/1.1 specifications and secondly to write and refine future HTTP/2 specifications (named httpbis).
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2009, Google announced SPDY – a binary protocol they developed to speed up web traffic between browsers and servers.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In many tests, using SPDY was indeed faster than using HTTP/1.1.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] SPDY was integrated into Google's Chromium and then into other major web browsers.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] Some of the ideas about multiplexing HTTP streams over a single TCP connection were taken from various sources, including the work of W3C HTTP-NG Working Group.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2012, HTTP Working Group (HTTPbis) announced the need for a new protocol; initially considering aspects of SPDY and eventually deciding to derive the new protocol from SPDY.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In May 2015, HTTP/2 was published as RFC 7540.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] The protocol was quickly adopted by web browsers already supporting SPDY and more slowly by web servers.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] As of 2022, HTTP/0.9 support has not been officially, completely deprecated and is still present in many web servers and browsers (for server responses only), even if usually disabled.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] It is unclear how long it will take to decommission HTTP/0.9.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In 2020, the first drafts of HTTP/3 were published and major web browsers and web servers started to adopt it.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] On 6 June 2022, IETF standardized HTTP/3 as RFC 9114.
[src:node-fetch-http/hypertext-transfer-protocol] In June 2022, RFC documents were published that deprecated many of the previous documents and introducing a few minor changes and a refactoring of HTTP semantics description into a separate document.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] A light-weight module that brings Fetch API to Node.js.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Instead of implementing `XMLHttpRequest` in Node.js to run browser-specific Fetch polyfill, why not go from native `http` to `fetch` API directly?
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Hence, `node-fetch`, minimal code for a `window.fetch` compatible API on Node.js runtime.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] See Jason Miller's isomorphic-unfetch or Leonardo Quixada's cross-fetch for isomorphic usage (exports `node-fetch` for server-side, `whatwg-fetch` for client-side).
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Current stable release (`3.x`) requires at least Node.js 12.20.0.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] `node-fetch` from v3 is an ESM-only module - you are not able to import it with `require()`.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] If you cannot switch to ESM, please use v2 which remains compatible with CommonJS.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Critical bug fixes will continue to be published for v2.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] NOTE: The documentation below is up-to-date with `3.x` releases, if you are using an older version, please check how to upgrade.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] `URLSearchParams` is available on the global object in Node.js as of v10.0.0.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] See official documentation for more usage methods.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] NOTE: 3xx-5xx responses are *NOT* exceptions, and should be handled in `then()`, see the next section.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Wrapping the fetch function into a `try/catch` block will catch *all* exceptions, such as errors originating from node core libraries, like network errors, and operational errors which are instances of FetchError.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] See the error handling document for more details.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] However, cookies can be extracted and passed by manipulating request and response headers.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] See Extract Set-Cookie Header for details.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] The "Node.js way" is to use streams when possible.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] You can pipe `res.body` to another stream.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] This example uses stream.pipeline to attach stream error handlers and wait for the download to complete.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] In Node.js 14 you can also use async iterators to read `body`; however, be careful to catch errors -- the longer a response runs, the more likely it is to encounter an error.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] In Node.js 12 you can also use async iterators to read `body`; however, async iterators with streams did not mature until Node.js 14, so you need to do some extra work to ensure you handle errors directly from the stream and wait on it response to fully close.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Unlike browsers, you can access raw `Set-Cookie` headers manually using `Headers.raw()`.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] If you for some reason need to post a stream coming from any arbitrary place, then you can append a Blob or a File look-a-like item.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] And either a `stream()` method or a `arrayBuffer()` method that returns a ArrayBuffer.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] The `stream()` must return any async iterable object as long as it yields Uint8Array (or Buffer) so Node.Readable streams and whatwg streams works just fine.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] You may cancel requests with `AbortController`.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] A suggested implementation is `abort-controller`.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] `url` should be an absolute URL, such as `https://example.com/`.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] A path-relative URL (`/file/under/root`) or protocol-relative URL (`//can-be-http-or-https.com/`) will result in a rejected `Promise`.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] The default values are shown after each option key.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Note: when `body` is a `Stream`, `Content-Length` is not set automatically.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] If no agent is specified, the default agent provided by Node.js is used.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Note that this changed in Node.js 19 to have `keepalive` true by default.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] If you wish to enable `keepalive` in an earlier version of Node.js, you can override the agent as per the following code sample.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] In addition, the `agent` option accepts a function that returns `http`(s)`.Agent` instance given current URL, this is useful during a redirection chain across HTTP and HTTPS protocol.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Stream on Node.js have a smaller internal buffer size (16kB, aka `highWaterMark`) from client-side browsers (>1MB, not consistent across browsers).
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Because of that, when you are writing an isomorphic app and using `res.clone()`, it will hang with large response in Node.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Passed through to the `insecureHTTPParser` option on http(s).request.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] See `http.request` for more information.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] The `redirect: 'manual'` option for node-fetch is different from the browser & specification, which results in an opaque-redirect filtered response. node-fetch gives you the typical basic filtered response instead.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] An HTTP(S) request containing information about URL, method, headers, and the body.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] This class implements the Body interface.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] See options for exact meaning of these extensions.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] The constructor is identical to that in the browser.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] In most cases, directly `fetch(url, options)` is simpler than creating a `Request` object.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Because Node.js does not implement service workers (for which this class was designed), one rarely has to construct a `Response` directly.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Convenience property representing if the request ended normally.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Will evaluate to true if the response status was greater than or equal to 200 but smaller than 300.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Convenience property representing if the request has been redirected at least once.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Will evaluate to true if the internal redirect counter is greater than 0.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Convenience property representing the response's type. node-fetch only supports `'default'` and `'error'` and does not make use of filtered responses.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] This class allows manipulating and iterating over a set of HTTP headers.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] All methods specified in the Fetch Standard are implemented.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] `init` can be either `null`, a `Headers` object, an key-value map object or any iterable object.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] `Body` is an abstract interface with methods that are applicable to both `Request` and `Response` classes.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Data are encapsulated in the `Body` object.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Note that while the Fetch Standard requires the property to always be a WHATWG `ReadableStream`, in node-fetch it is a Node.js `Readable` stream.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] A boolean property for if this body has been consumed.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Per the specs, a consumed body cannot be used again.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] `fetch` comes with methods to parse `multipart/form-data` payloads as well as `x-www-form-urlencoded` bodies using `.formData()` this comes from the idea that Service Worker can intercept such messages before it's sent to the server to alter them.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] This is useful for anybody building a server so you can use it to parse & consume payloads.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] An operational error in the fetching process.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] An Error thrown when the request is aborted in response to an `AbortSignal`'s `abort` event.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] It has a `name` property of `AbortError`.
[src:node-fetch-http/node-fetch-node-fetch] Thanks to github/fetch for providing a solid implementation reference.
